<br>
1) National Defense <br>
2) Enforcement of Contracts. <br>
<br>
The rationale for even this low level of gov't intervention in peoples lives is still based on the social contract theory you mention. This is, however, 18th century social contract theory developed largely by men of power and position with democratic urges in the face of monarchists of the day who reigned and seized wealth capriciously to raises armies and provide for themselves and their subjects from some type of divine right justification. <br>
<br>
This capriciousness on the behalf of the crown just didnt sit well with these American colonial leaders OR with anti-monarchists of the day in Europe. Do not forget that the American revolution, the French revolution, and subsequent machinations leading all the way up to WWI, are largely the unraveling of monarchies everywhere. Political authority was not resident in an individual any longer. That was viewed as illegitimate. <br>
<br>
I think by and large the movements against the crown in America were from what Marx called the bourgesie(sp?) and the upper class landholders. These people wanted elected parliaments to decided when and if taxes where to be levied for purposes that they had some control over. <br>
<br>
Nowhere in all of this was a concern for the peasant in regard to his position vis-a-vis the social contract of governance.<br>
<br>
As countries, including the US and all across Europe, passed through the Industrial Revolution and urban centers became the population loci for various societies, changes began to occur which began the process of broadening the meaning and stake in the social contract for men and women of lower class status. <br>
<br>
Along with World wide conflicts in WWI and WWII, bringing people of various groups closer to each other had many consequences. To make a long story on the broadening of political rights for minorities, women and the like, shorter....these new franchised groups understood that those from whom they were asking a fairer shake were not in a position to grant them an equal result. <br>
<br>
These emerging groups wanted genuine opportunity. They wanted to attend the allwhite schools, own property themselves wherever they wanted, and to not be confined by there gender to particular life possibilities. <br>
<br>
These groups of people did not expect the government to return to them as a part of their new social contract, equality of outcome. <br>
<br>
Certainly social contracts are not homogeneous in result for all. They will never mean the same thing for me as for John Rockefeller. But if &quot;the game&quot; was restarted tomorrow with neither Rockefeller or myself knowing where we would &quot;Start&quot; so to speak, it is a lock that both of us would first like to sacrifice our natural state of complete freedom only if after our safety needs our met, that our goverment could provide an equality of opportunity for each of us. <br>
<br>
And from equality of opportunity it is natural that the justly earned rewards of our efforts should be next in line of importance relative to being free from government confiscation. The valuable and necessary &quot;incentive&quot; portion of our equality of opportunity requires that the government entity subsequently respect our property. <br>
<br>
Think about it this way:  How could I have equality of opportunity if my earnings were subject to the caprice of confiscation by either a king or a parliament OR a Marxian state that seized the same because as the owners of production they laid claim to the fruits of my labor?  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jhardzia>jhardzia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/22/03 4:22:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question for the Libertarians</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Something I did learn soon after purchasing land. I may own the land but, If I don't purchase the mineral rights a coal/geology group can purchase them and come in and mine my property. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
